│ An LLVM bug is causing an incorrect transformation in the    │
│ `instcombine` pass, where a `select` instruction with the    │
│ `nsz` (no signed zeros) fast-math flag is improperly folded  │
│ into an `fmin` operation. This miscompilation occurs because │
│ `fmin` (which lowers to `llvm.minnum`) has stricter          │
│ semantics regarding signed zeros than the original `select`  │
│ with `nsz`. Specifically, `llvm.minnum(+0.0, -0.0)` must     │
│ return `-0.0`, while the original `select` could return      │
│ `+0.0`.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ The root of the issue lies in the `matchFMinFMax` helper     │
│ function within `InstCombineSelect.cpp`. This function fails │
│ to account for the `nsz` flag when matching operands,        │
│ leading to the faulty transformation.                        │
│                                                              │
│ To fix this, I will modify `matchFMinFMax` to use a more     │
│ relaxed operand comparison when the `nsz` flag is present.   │
│ This will be achieved by using `isIdenticalToOrSplatOf`,     │
│ which correctly treats `+0.0` and `-0.0` as equivalent under │
│ `nsz`, thus preventing the incorrect folding.                │
│                                                              │
