│ The issue is that `m_OrdOrUnordFMin` and `m_OrdOrUnordFMax`  │
│ do not respect the `nsz` flag. The matcher logic needs to be │
│ more careful. The `nsz` flag on the `select` is not          │
│ sufficient to guarantee that the transformation to           │
│ `minnum`/`maxnum` is correct because the `fcmp` may not have │
│ `nsz`.                                                       │
│                                                              │
│ The correct fix is to check that the `fcmp` also has `nsz`.  │
│                                                              │
│ I will modify the `m_OrdOrUnordFMin` and `m_OrdOrUnordFMax`  │
│ matchers to check for the `nsz` flag on the `fcmp`.          │
│                                                              │
│ Looking at the code again, the check for `nsz` is on the     │
│ `select` (`SIFPOp`), but the `fcmp` is what determines the   │
│ signed zero behavior in the original code. The `nsz` on the  │
│ `select` is not enough. The `fcmp` must also have `nsz`.     │
│                                                              │
│ The logic should be: if we are doing a min/max transform,    │
│ and the select has `nsz`, then the `fcmp` must also have     │
│ `nsz`.                                                       │
│                                                              │
│ The current logic is:                                        │
│ `SIFPOp->hasNoSignedZeros()` which is true for the           │
│ reproducer.                                                  │
│ The `FCmp` is not checked for `nsz`.                         │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to add a check for `FCmp->hasNoSignedZeros()`     │
│ when `SIFPOp->hasNoSignedZeros()` is true.                   │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // In InstCombinerImpl::visitSelectInst                      │
│ ...                                                          │
│     if (SIFPOp->hasNoNaNs() &&                               │
│         (SIFPOp->hasNoSignedZeros() ||                       │
│          (SIFPOp->hasOneUse() &&                             │
│           canIgnoreSignBitOfZero(*SIFPOp->use_begin())))) {  │
│ ...                                                          │
│ ```                                                          │
│ The `FCmp` is available at this point. The check should be:  │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│     if (SIFPOp->hasNoNaNs() &&                               │
│         ((FCmp && FCmp->hasNoSignedZeros() &&                │
│ SIFPOp->hasNoSignedZeros()) ||                               │
│          (SIFPOp->hasOneUse() &&                             │
│           canIgnoreSignBitOfZero(*SIFPOp->use_begin())))) {  │
│ ```                                                          │
