│ An LLVM bug is causing an incorrect transformation in the    │
│ `instcombine` pass, where a `select` instruction with the    │
│ `nsz` (no signed zeros) fast-math flag is improperly folded  │
│ into an `fmin` operation. This miscompilation occurs because │
│ `fmin` (which lowers to `llvm.minnum`) has stricter          │
│ semantics regarding signed zeros than the original `select`  │
│ with `nsz`. Specifically, `llvm.minnum(+0.0, -0.0)` must     │
│ return `-0.0`, while the original `select` could return      │
│ `+0.0`.                                                      │
│                                                              │
│ The root of the issue lies in the                            │
│ `InstCombinerImpl::visitSelectInst` function within          │
│ `InstCombineSelect.cpp`. This function attempts to fold a    │
│ `select` into a `minnum`/`maxnum` intrinsic but fails to     │
│ correctly account for the `nsz` flag. The transformation to  │
│ `minnum`/`maxnum` is only valid if signed zeros can be       │
│ ignored by consumers of the `select`, or if the `fcmp`       │
│ condition itself does not have the `nsz` flag. The current   │
│ logic incorrectly allows the transformation even when the    │
│ `fcmp` has `nsz`, leading to the miscompilation.             │
│                                                              │
│ To fix this, I will adjust the conditional logic that guards │
│ this transformation. The transform will be disallowed if the │
│ `select`'s condition is an `fcmp` with the `nsz` flag set.   │
│ This ensures that the semantically incorrect folding to      │
│ `minnum`/`maxnum` does not occur in cases where signed zero  │
│ behavior differs.                                            │
